rs]]\n[[Category:20th-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Sabuj Arjo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kamal_Ahmed_(singer)"}
{"title_page": "Jo Vincent", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name                 = Jo Vincent\n| image                = JoVincent1953.jpg\n| image_upright        = 1.3\n| caption              = Jo Vincent onstage in 1953\n| birth_name           = Johanna Maria Vincent\n| birth_date           = {{birth date|1898|03|06|df=y}}\n| death_date           = {{death date and age|1989|11|28|1898|03|06|df=y}}\n| occupation           = [[Soprano]] \n}}\n'''Johanna Maria (Jo) Vincent''' (6 March 1898&nbsp;\u2013 28 November 1989) was a Dutch [[soprano]] who appeared mostly in [[oratorio]] and concert, and is internationally known. She appeared regularly with [[Willem Mengelberg]] and the [[Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra]] from 1924 to 1942, including annual concerts and a recording of Bach's ''[[St Matthew Passion]]''. She participated in the world premiere of [[Benjamin Britten]]'s ''[[Spring Symphony]]'', with [[Kathleen Ferrier]] and [[Peter Pears]]. After retiring, she taught at the Haarlem Conservatory.\n\n== Life ==\nJohanna Vincent was born in [[Amsterdam]], the daughter of the organist, piano teacher and carilloneur Jacob Vincent, and Geertruida Johanna Meijer.<ref name=\"Jonge\" /> At age nine, she joined the children's choir of [[Catharina van Rennes]].<ref name=\"Jonge\" /> She studied to be a voice teacher, graduating with a diploma in 1919. She gave singing lessons to pay for studying voice with [[Corn\u00e9lie van Zanten]].<ref name=\"Jonge\" />\n\nHer first public concert was in [[Assendelft]] in 1920. She first appeared with the [[Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra]] in 1923, conducted by [[Cornelis Dopper]].<ref name=\"Jonge\" /> Vincent focused on a repertoire of [[oratorio]], especially [[Passions (Bach)|Bach's Passions]], and [[lied]]er by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]], [[Gustav Mahler]], [[Franz Schubert]] and [[Hugo Wolf]]. Vincent sang frequently in concerts with [[Willem Mengelberg]] and the Concertgebouw Orchestra, first in 1924 in a concert with songs by G. H. G. von Brucken Fock, and Mahler's [[Symphony No. 8 (Mahler)|Eighth Symphony]], which was broadcast.<ref name=\"Jonge\" /> From 1932, she was the soprano soloist in Bach's ''[[St Matthew Passion]]'', which Mengelberg had conducted annually on [[Palm Sunday]] since 1899. She appeared in the 1939 early recording of this Passion, which featured [[Karl Erb]] as the [[Evangelist (Bach)|Evangelist]], [[Willem Ravelli]] as the [[Vox Christi]], and other soloists [[Ilona Durigo]], [[Louis van Tulder]] and {{ill|Hermann Schey|de}}.<ref name=\"Walker\" /> Their concerts ended in 1942, due to the [[German occupation of the Netherlands|German occupation]].<ref name=\"Walker\" />\n\nVincent occasionally appeared internationally, such as in Paris in 1929, performing as Margu\u00e9rite in ''[[La damnation de Faust]]'' by Berlioz, conducted by [[Pierre Monteux]], in Vienna in 1932 where Mengelberg conducted Mahler's [[Symphony No. 4 (Mahler)|Fourth Symphony]], and also in Vienna in 1936 in Beethoven's [[Missa solemnis (Beethoven)|Missa solemnis]]. Her only operatic role was the Countess in Mozart's ''[[Le nozze di Figaro]]'',<ref name=\"Walker\" /> performed in 1939 in Scheveningen.<ref name=\"Jonge\" /> In London, she appeared at [[The Proms]] several times between 1939 and 1948,<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/bf724e97-715c-4fb6-b652-23a972363579 Jo Vincent] [[BBC]]</ref> then performed in [[Queen's Hall]], conducted by [[Henry Wood (conductor)|Henry Wood]].<ref name=\"Jonge\" />\n\nOn 14 July 1949, she took part in the world premiere of Benjamin Britten's ''[[Spring Symphony]]'' at the Concertgebouw as part of the [[Holland Festival]], with contralto [[Kathleen Ferrier]], tenor [[Peter Pears]], and conducted by [[Eduard van Beinum]].<ref name=\"Britten\" /> A review in ''New Statesman and Nation'' dated 23 July 1949 stated that Vincent \"excelled herself\" in bird songs.<ref name=\"Britten\" /> A recording of the first performance was first issued by [[Decca Records|Decca]] in August 1994.<ref name=\"Gramophone\" />\n\nVincent retired in 1953, after which she gave occasional performances. After retirement, she taught singing from 1955 to 1956 at the Haarlem Conservatory.<ref name=\"Jonge\" /> She died on 28 November 1989 in [[Monaco]].<ref name=\"Jonge\" />\n\n== Recordings ==\nVincent's voice appears on several recordings:<ref>[http://www.arkivmusic.com/classical/albumList.jsp?name_id1=36790&name_role1=2&bcorder=2 Jo Vincent] ArkivMusic</ref><ref>[https://www.muziekweb.nl/Link/M00000257891/CLASSICAL/Jo-Vincent Jo Vincen] (in Dutch) muziekweb.nl</ref>\n<!--[[Bestand:PDP-CH - Jo Vincent - Ave Maria - Bach - Gounod - Columbia-11805-fx215.flac|thumb|''[[Ave Maria (Bach/Gounod)|Ave Maria]]'' (Jo Vincent)]]-->\n* ''Jo Vincent CD1'' \n* ''Jo Vincent, Philips Legendary Voices''. CDs\n* ''Jo Vincent, The Great Dutch Soprano''. CDs \n* ''Jo Vincent Kwartet - Psalmen en Gezangen / Liederen van Joh. de Heer''\n* ''Jo Vincent - Passion, Oratorio & Arias'', 2 CD's\n* Mahler: [[Symphony No. 2 (Mahler)|Symphony No. 2]] \"Resurrection\", [[Kathleen Ferrier]], [[Otto Klemperer]]\n* Mahler: [[Symphony No. 4 (Mahler)|Symphony No. 4]], Mengelberg<ref name=\"Smoley\" />\n\n== Further reading ==\n* C. G. J. Bos: ''Jo Vincent - Zingend door het leven'' (memoir)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Britten\">{{cite book\n| last = Britten\n| first = Benjamin\n| authorlink = Benjamin Britten\n| editor-last = Mitchell\n| editor-first = Donald\n| editor-last2 = Red\n| editor-first2 = Philip\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=22OPd1_ISNsC&pg=PT492\n| title = Letters from a Life Volume 3 (1946-1951): The Selected Letters of Benjamin Britten\n| publisher = [[Faber & Faber]]\n| volume = 3\n| date = 2011\n| isbn = 978-0-57-127993-7\n| page = 492\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Jonge\">{{cite book\n| last = Jonge\n| first = A. W. J. de\n| url = http://resources.huygens.knaw.nl/bwn1880-2000/lemmata/bwn4/vincejm\n| title = Vincent, Johanna Maria (1898-1989)\n| website = resources.huygens.knaw.nl\n| date = 1994\n| accessdate = 3 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Smoley\">{{cite book\n| last = Smoley\n| first = Lewis M.\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Q3dy15LA4eQC&pg=PA95\n| title = Gustav Mahler's Symphonies: Critical Commentary on Recordings Since 1986\n| publisher = [[Greenwood Publishing Group]]\n| date = 1996\n| isbn = 978-0-31-329771-7\n| page = 95\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Walker\">{{cite web\n| last = Walker\n| first = Malcolm\n| url = https://www.naxos.com/mainsite/blurbs_reviews.asp?item_code=8.110880-82&catNum=8110880&filetype=About%20this%20Recording&language=English\n| title = Bach, J. S.: St. Matthew Passion (Mengelberg) (1939)\n| website = [[Naxos Records]]\n| date = \n| accessdate = 3 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gramophone\">{{cite journal\n| url = https://www.gramophone.co.uk/review/britten-spring-symphony-etc-0\n| title = Britten Spring Symphony etc\n| journal = [[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]\n| date = September 1994\n| accessdate = 3 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat|Jo Vincent}}\n* {{DNB portal|134634349}}\n* [http://www.muziekencyclopedie.nl/action/entry/Jo+Vincent Jo Vincent] (in Dutch) muziekencyclopedie.nl\n* [http://www.historici.nl/Onderzoek/Projecten/BWN/lemmata/bwn4/vincejm Johanna Maria Vincent (1898-1989)] historici.nl\n* {{discogs artist}}\n* [https://www.bach-cantatas.com/Bio/Vincent-Jo.htm Jo Vincent (Soprano] Bach Cantatas Website\n* {{youtube|m6HXXKdTmK8|Jo Vincent sings Reger (Maria Wiegenlied)}}\n* {{youtube|8ZlfWj6JcO0|Kathleen Ferrier; Jo Vincent; Peter Pears; \"Spring Symphony\"; Benjamin Britten}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vincent, Jo}}\n[[Category:Dutch sopranos]]\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1989 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name                 = Jo Vincent\n| image                = JoVincent1953.jpg\n| image_upright        = 1.3\n| caption              = Jo Vincent onstage in 1953\n| birth_name           = Johanna Maria Vincent\n| birth_date           = {{birth date|1898|03|06|df=y}}\n| death_date           = {{death date and age|1989|11|28|1898|03|06|df=y}}\n| occupation           = [[Soprano]] \n}}\n'''Johanna Maria (Jo) Vincent''' (6 March 1898 \u2013 28 November 1989) was a Dutch [[soprano]] who appeared mostly in [[oratorio]] and concert, and is internationally known. She appeared regularly with [[Willem Mengelberg]] and the [[Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra]] from 1924 to 1942, including annual concerts and a recording of Bach's ''[[St Matthew Passion]]''. She participated in the world premiere of [[Benjamin Britten]]'s ''[[Spring Symphony]]'', with [[Kathleen Ferrier]] and [[Peter Pears]]. After retiring, she taught at the Haarlem Conservatory.\n\n== Life ==\nJohanna Vincent was born in [[Amsterdam]], the daughter of the organist, piano teacher and carilloneur Jacob Vincent, and Geertruida Johanna Meijer.<ref name=\"Jonge\" /> At age nine, she joined the children's choir of [[Catharina van Rennes]].<ref name=\"Jonge\" /> She studied to be a voice teacher, graduating with a diploma in 1919. She gave singing lessons to pay for studying voice with [[Corn\u00e9lie van Zanten]].<ref name=\"Jonge\" />\n\nHer first public concert was in [[Assendelft]] in 1920. She first appeared with the [[Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra]] in 1923, conducted by [[Cornelis Dopper]].<ref name=\"Jonge\" /> Vincent focused on a repertoire of [[oratorio]], especially [[Passions (Bach)|Bach's Passions]], and [[lied]]er by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]], [[Gustav Mahler]], [[Franz Schubert]] and [[Hugo Wolf]]. Vincent sang frequently in concerts with [[Willem Mengelberg]] and the Concertgebouw Orchestra, first in 1924 in a concert with songs by G. H. G. von Brucken Fock, and Mahler's [[Symphony No. 8 (Mahler)|Eighth Symphony]], which was broadcast.<ref name=\"Jonge\" /> From 1932, she was the soprano soloist in Bach's ''[[St Matthew Passion]]'', which Mengelberg had conducted annually on [[Palm Sunday]] since 1899. She appeared in the 1939 early recording of this Passion, which featured [[Karl Erb]] as the [[Evangelist (Bach)|Evangelist]], [[Willem Ravelli]] as the [[Vox Christi]], and other soloists [[Ilona Durigo]], [[Louis van Tulder]] and {{ill|Hermann Schey|de}}.<ref name=\"Walker\" /> Their concerts ended in 1942, due to the [[German occupation of the Netherlands|German occupation]].<ref name=\"Walker\" />\n\nVincent occasionally appeared internationally, such as in Paris in 1929, performing as Margu\u00e9rite in ''[[La damnation de Faust]]'' by Berlioz, conducted by [[Pierre Monteux]], in Vienna in 1932 where Mengelberg conducted Mahler's [[Symphony No. 4 (Mahler)|Fourth Symphony]], and also in Vienna in 1936 in Beethoven's [[Missa solemnis (Beethoven)|Missa solemnis]]. Her only operatic role was the Countess in Mozart's ''[[Le nozze di Figaro]]'',<ref name=\"Walker\" /> performed in 1939 in Scheveningen.<ref name=\"Jonge\" />  In London, she appeared at [[The Proms]] several times between 1939 and 1948,<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/bf724e97-715c-4fb6-b652-23a972363579 Jo Vincent] [[BBC]]</ref> then performed in [[Queen's Hall]], conducted by [[Henry Wood (conductor)|Henry Wood]].<ref name=\"Jonge\" />\n\nOn 14 July 1949, she took part in the world premiere of Benjamin Britten's ''[[Spring Symphony]]'' at the Concertgebouw as part of the [[Holland Festival]], with contralto [[Kathleen Ferrier]], tenor [[Peter Pears]], and conducted by [[Eduard van Beinum]].<ref name=\"Britten\" /> A review in ''New Statesman and Nation'' dated 23 July 1949 stated that Vincent \"excelled herself\" in bird songs.<ref name=\"Britten\" /> A recording of the first performance was first issued by [[Decca Records|Decca]] in August 1994.<ref name=\"Gramophone\" />\n\nVincent retired in 1953, after which she gave occasional performances. After retirement, she taught singing from 1955 to 1956 at the Haarlem Conservatory.<ref name=\"Jonge\" /> She died on 28 November 1989 in [[Monaco]].<ref name=\"Jonge\" />\n\n== Recordings ==\nVincent's voice appears on several recordings:<ref>[http://www.arkivmusic.com/classical/albumList.jsp?name_id1=36790&name_role1=2&bcorder=2 Jo Vincent] ArkivMusic</ref><ref>[https://www.muziekweb.nl/Link/M00000257891/CLASSICAL/Jo-Vincent Jo Vincen] (in Dutch) muziekweb.nl</ref>\n<!--[[Bestand:PDP-CH - Jo Vincent - Ave Maria - Bach - Gounod - Columbia-11805-fx215.flac|thumb|''[[Ave Maria (Bach/Gounod)|Ave Maria]]'' (Jo Vincent)]]-->\n* ''Jo Vincent CD1'' \n* ''Jo Vincent, Philips Legendary Voices''. CDs\n* ''Jo Vincent, The Great Dutch Soprano''. CDs \n* ''Jo Vincent Kwartet - Psalmen en Gezangen / Liederen van Joh. de Heer''\n* ''Jo Vincent - Passion, Oratorio & Arias'', 2 CD's\n* Mahler: [[Symphony No. 2 (Mahler)|Symphony No. 2]] \"Resurrection\", [[Kathleen Ferrier]], [[Otto Klemperer]]\n* Mahler: [[Symphony No. 4 (Mahler)|Symphony No. 4]], Mengelberg<ref name=\"Smoley\" />\n\n== Further reading ==\n* C. G. J. Bos: ''Jo Vincent - Zingend door het leven'' (memoir)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Britten\">{{cite book\n| last = Britten\n| first = Benjamin\n| authorlink = Benjamin Britten\n| editor-last = Mitchell\n| editor-first = Donald\n| editor-last2 = Red\n| editor-first2 = Philip\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=22OPd1_ISNsC&pg=PT492\n| title = Letters from a Life Volume 3 (1946-1951): The Selected Letters of Benjamin Britten\n| publisher = [[Faber & Faber]]\n| volume = 3\n| date = 2011\n| isbn = 978-0-57-127993-7\n| page = 492\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Jonge\">{{cite book\n| last = Jonge\n| first = A. W. J. de\n| url = http://resources.huygens.knaw.nl/bwn1880-2000/lemmata/bwn4/vincejm\n| title = Vincent, Johanna Maria (1898-1989)\n| website = resources.huygens.knaw.nl\n| date = 1994\n| accessdate = 3 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Smoley\">{{cite book\n| last = Smoley\n| first = Lewis M.\n| url = https://books.google.com/boo